Chet and Doc:<br><br>
If Vietnam Veterans were a &quot;race&quot;, I feel those people would qualfy as &quot;racists&quot;. It seems to be a peculiarity of some individuals to invalidate those who appear to represent or trigger something inside with which they would rather not address. I think another appropriate word would be a &quot;trigger&quot;. <br><br>
Like our &quot;friend&quot; Paul on site 50, rewriting history seems to be a passion. What on earth could be bothering people so much that a lie is more comforting? Perhaps it is our truth that is disturbing.<br><br>
I had the rare and distinct honor a while back to interact with a Mennonite CO on issues like this, and his feeling was that Vietnam Veterans had a &quot;special&quot; insight into the American soul. I guess it is that we are compelled to look deeply into ourselves past the trappings of society to rediscover who we are to be able to come to grips with that which haunts us so.<br><br>
Whatever the reason, I feel some of these individuals are worse than any &quot;protestor&quot; I have met, even the worst. Perhaps I am recovering the feelings of the true meaning of &quot;evil&quot;.<br><br>
I refuse to allow their agenda to rule my life or inhibit my free expression of feelings and facts about my Vietnam experience. I think too highly of myself now to allow that to happen.<br><br>
Chet, I am pissed off as well. <br><br>
Doc, you seem to have contact with them. Invite them over for a chat. We will soon discover the courage of their convictions.
